<P>
All Aboard Aren't Human 
</P>
<P>
Yes, those were mice you saw darting beneath the seats on the Amtrak train 
between San Diego and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Mice are a continual problem aboard the trains, and Amtrak has a year-round 
contract with an exterminator. It's the food, not the travel, that lures the 
mice. 
</P>
<P>
"Some people are slobs and leave all kinds of food scraps on the train," 
explained Amtrak spokesman Arthur Lloyd. "The San Diego-to-L.A. train usually 
makes two round trips a day and isn't cleaned thoroughly until the end of the 
day. The mice can eat quite well until the exterminator gets them." 
</P>
<P>
The freeloading rodents also have a preference for riding first-class. 
</P>
